    duration: '50 min',
    content: `
<h2>Presenting Your Findings Effectively</h2>

<p>The way you present your findings can make the difference between an investigation that merely describes data and one that genuinely illuminates a linguistic phenomenon. Clear, well-organised presentation helps the examiner follow your argument, understand your evidence, and appreciate the quality of your analysis. This module covers the practical and analytical skills you need to present your findings in a way that is both rigorous and persuasive.</p>

<h3>Organising Your Analysis</h3>

<p>Before you begin writing, decide on the <strong>organisational structure</strong> of your analysis section. There are several effective approaches. You might organise by <strong>linguistic level</strong>, examining your data first through a phonological lens, then through a lexical lens, then through a grammatical lens, and so on. This works well when your research question is broad enough to warrant multi-level analysis. Alternatively, you might organise by <strong>theme or finding</strong>, grouping your observations around the main patterns or trends you have identified in your data. This works well when your findings cluster naturally into distinct categories. A third option is to organise by <strong>data source</strong>, analysing each text, transcript, or data set in turn and drawing comparisons between them. This works well for comparative investigations.</p>

<p>Whichever structure you choose, ensure that your analysis is <strong>integrated</strong> rather than fragmented. Each section or paragraph should build on what came before and connect to what follows. Use clear topic sentences at the start of each paragraph, and use signposting language ("The most striking finding was...," "However, a contrasting pattern emerged in...," "This supports the hypothesis that...") to guide the examiner through your argument.</p>

<h3>Using Tables and Charts</h3>

<p>Quantitative data is most effectively presented in <strong>tables</strong> and <strong>charts</strong>. A well-designed table can display a large amount of data in a compact, accessible format. Use tables to present frequency counts, percentages, comparisons across categories, and summaries of your quantitative findings. Every table should have a clear title, labelled columns and rows, and should be referenced in your written analysis — do not insert a table and leave it unexplained.</p>

<p><strong>Bar charts</strong> are effective for comparing discrete categories (e.g., the frequency of hedges used by male versus female speakers). <strong>Pie charts</strong> can show proportions within a single category (e.g., the percentage of different sentence types in a text). <strong>Line graphs</strong> are useful for showing change over time or across a continuous variable. Choose the chart type that most clearly communicates the pattern you want to highlight. Keep charts simple and uncluttered — avoid three-dimensional effects, excessive colour, or decorative elements that distract from the data.</p>

<div class="examiner-tip"><strong>Examiner Tip:</strong> Tables and charts should support your analysis, not replace it. Inserting a table without discussing what it shows is a wasted opportunity. After presenting quantitative data, always explain the patterns, comment on the significance of the numbers, and connect them to your research question and to relevant linguistic theory.</div>

<h3>Integrating Quantitative and Qualitative Analysis</h3>

<p>The most effective investigations use quantitative data to identify patterns and qualitative analysis to explore what those patterns mean. A productive approach is to present your quantitative findings first — perhaps in a table showing the frequency of a particular feature across your data set — and then select the most interesting or significant examples for close qualitative analysis. This "zoom in" technique allows you to demonstrate both the breadth of your investigation and the depth of your analytical skills.</p>

<p>For example, your table might show that Speaker A uses three times as many imperative structures as Speaker B during a workplace meeting. The quantitative finding establishes the pattern; your qualitative analysis then examines specific imperatives in context: what pragmatic function do they serve? Are they softened with politeness markers? How do other participants respond to them? This integration of numbers and interpretation produces a compelling, well-rounded analysis.</p>

<h3>Using Quotations from Data</h3>

<p>When discussing specific examples from your data, <strong>quote directly</strong> from your transcripts or texts. Use a consistent referencing system — for example, numbering the lines of your transcript and referring to them as "line 14" or "lines 22–25." For written texts, indicate the source clearly. When quoting spoken data, reproduce your transcription conventions consistently (including pause lengths, overlaps, and emphasis markers if relevant). Embed quotations within your analytical sentences rather than letting them stand alone — for example, "Speaker B's hedged response in line 14 ('I might sort of try and do that') combines epistemic modality with vague language, distancing herself from commitment."</p>

<h3>Appendices and Data Presentation</h3>

<p>Your raw data — full transcripts, copies of written texts, completed questionnaires, corpus outputs — should be included in <strong>appendices</strong> at the end of your investigation. Appendices do not count towards your word limit, so include whatever data the examiner would need to verify your analysis. Label your appendices clearly (Appendix A, Appendix B, etc.) and reference them in the main body of your investigation when you draw on specific data. Your transcripts should include a key explaining any transcription symbols you have used.</p>

<h3>Visual Presentation</h3>

<p>The visual presentation of your investigation matters. Use clear headings and subheadings to structure your report. Use consistent formatting for quotations, tables, and data references. Ensure that your investigation is easy to navigate — the examiner should be able to find your introduction, methodology, analysis, and conclusion quickly and clearly. While visual presentation alone will not earn you marks, poor presentation can obscure good analysis and make it harder for the examiner to follow your argument.</p>

<div class="common-mistake"><strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Including large amounts of raw data in the main body of the investigation without analysis. Raw transcripts, full questionnaire results, and lengthy corpus outputs belong in the appendices. The main body should contain analysed data — specific, selected examples discussed in depth with reference to linguistic frameworks and your research question.</div>

<h3>Signposting Your Argument</h3>

<p>Use <strong>discourse markers</strong> and <strong>signposting language</strong> to make your argument explicit. Phrases like "This finding supports...," "Conversely...," "The most significant pattern to emerge was...," "This is consistent with [theorist's] claim that...," and "However, the data also reveals..." help the examiner follow the logical thread of your analysis. An investigation that presents a series of disconnected observations will score lower than one that builds a coherent, cumulative argument towards a clear conclusion.</p>
`,
